# Git line-ending & diff policy for Psiphon-3X-UI.
#
# WHY: On Windows dev hosts ``core.autocrlf=true`` converts LF ↔ CRLF on
# checkout/commit. That's fine for code (IDEs cope) BUT it means the SHA256
# of the working-tree copy of an artefact differs from the SHA256 of the
# git blob (which is LF-canonical). raw.githubusercontent.com serves the
# git blob, so the operator-facing ``sha256sum -c release-artifacts.sha256``
# verification must compute the same hash the operator sees after a fresh
# ``git clone`` — i.e. the LF-canonical hash, not the working-tree hash.
#
# Pinning ``eol=lf`` for the SHIPPED artefacts (install scripts, panel HTML,
# i18n JSON, manifest itself) keeps those hashes stable across hosts without
# retraining contributors' editors. Source Python/JS/etc. inherit git's
# default text handling.
#
# To re-normalise the working tree after editing this file:
#   git add --renormalize .
#   git commit -m "chore: enforce .gitattributes line-ending policy"

# ── Shipped operator-facing release artefacts (LF canonical) ──────────────
*.sh               text eol=lf
*.html             text eol=lf
*.css              text eol=lf
*.js               text eol=lf
*.json             text eol=lf
install.sh         text eol=lf
release-artifacts.sha256  text eol=lf

# ── Python source (default text = LF on commit) ─────────────────────────
*.py               text

# ── Documentation ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
*.md               text eol=lf

# ── Binary assets (no line-ending conversion) ───────────────────────────
*.png              binary
*.jpg              binary
*.ico              binary
*.svg              text eol=lf
*.woff2            binary
